00:52:35.840 --> 00:52:36.920
paranoid about inflation.

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:39.290
So I went and read a lot about
the German hyperinflation.

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:41.780
And it was deliberate government
policy to stuff the

00:52:41.780 --> 00:52:43.590
French over reparations.

00:52:43.590 --> 00:52:45.140
I mean, they did it quite
deliberately.

00:52:45.140 --> 00:52:47.600
And the weird about it was after
they did it, it ended in

00:52:47.600 --> 00:52:48.820
eight months.

00:52:48.820 --> 00:52:51.810
And the entire economy was
stabilized within 12.

00:52:51.810 --> 00:52:53.520
And then it grew
for five years.

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:55.660
And then what actually happened
was austerity,

00:52:55.660 --> 00:52:57.460
through the economy of a cliff,
and that's when the

00:52:57.460 --> 00:52:58.720
Nazis came to power.

00:52:58.720 --> 00:53:02.000
So we have this story about the
least degree of inflation

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:05.490
leads to some kind of infinity
curve hyper-convexity where,

00:53:05.490 --> 00:53:06.780
boom, off it goes.

00:53:06.780 --> 00:53:08.250
And it's simply not true.

00:53:08.250 --> 00:53:11.180
Post-war Europe ran positive
rates of inflation with

00:53:11.180 --> 00:53:13.530
positive real rates of growth
all the way through the

00:53:13.530 --> 00:53:16.070
postwar period until
about 1980.

00:53:16.070 --> 00:53:18.250
So the inflation
panic is there.

00:53:20.878 --> 00:53:25.220
AUDIENCE: So I've heard Krugman
and others bring up

00:53:25.220 --> 00:53:28.830
Japan as an example to support
these kind of arguments.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:31.260
Can you just talk a bit about
how they're able to run a high

00:53:31.260 --> 00:53:33.830
debt for so long and things
don't seem to--

00:53:33.830 --> 00:53:34.340
MARK BLYTH: Sure, sure.

00:53:34.340 --> 00:53:35.200
Absolutely.

00:53:35.200 --> 00:53:37.150
I actually think these guys
are wrong about Japan.

00:53:37.150 --> 00:53:39.650
I think what goes on in Japan is
actually deeply structural.

00:53:39.650 --> 00:53:42.110
There is a wonderful book by
guy called Sven Steinmo,

00:53:42.110 --> 00:53:44.160
called "The Evolution of the
Modern State." And he has a

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:45.180
chapter on Japan.

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:46.950
And if you ever wanted to read,
I think, the definitive

00:53:46.950 --> 00:53:48.350
story on Japan, this is it.

00:53:48.350 --> 00:53:51.180
He spent two years there on an
Abe fellowship and had access

00:53:51.180 --> 00:53:52.180
to all the people.

00:53:52.180 --> 00:53:52.725
Well, it was two books.

00:53:52.725 --> 00:53:55.310
It was Richard Koo's "Holy Grail
of Macroeconomics." So

00:53:55.310 --> 00:53:57.920
basically what happens is Japan
goes through a balance

00:53:57.920 --> 00:53:58.410
sheet recession.

00:53:58.410 --> 00:54:00.430
What's a balance sheet
recession?

00:54:00.430 --> 00:54:03.190
Basically, your companies are
de-levering but don't want to

00:54:03.190 --> 00:54:04.376
tell anyone because
if they do, there

00:54:04.376 --> 00:54:05.990
will be a run on them.

00:54:05.990 --> 00:54:08.160
And everybody's complicit
together because they've all

00:54:08.160 --> 00:54:08.950
over borrowed.

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:12.460
So basically, you have this
kind of slow bleeding that

00:54:12.460 --> 00:54:15.140
goes on as it's sort of
monetized by the central bank,

00:54:15.140 --> 00:54:16.490
and it ends up in debt.

00:54:16.490 --> 00:54:17.580
So you're not growing.

00:54:17.580 --> 00:54:20.840
And that's sort of the obvious
part of the story.

00:54:20.840 --> 00:54:22.860
The less obvious part of the
story goes like this.

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:24.070
Go back to 1986.

00:54:24.070 --> 00:54:25.050
There's a thing called
the Plaza Accord.

00:54:25.050 --> 00:54:27.305
The Plaza Accord was when the
United States turns around to

00:54:27.305 --> 00:54:29.450
its two major trading partners,
Japan and then West

00:54:29.450 --> 00:54:33.970
Germany, and said, our exchange
rate is too high.

00:54:33.970 --> 00:54:37.180
People are buying dollars, we're
doing well just now.

00:54:37.180 --> 00:54:38.360
And it's killing our exports.

00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:39.140
You guys are wiping us out.

00:54:39.140 --> 00:54:41.300
Remember the whole paranoia
about Japan that went on?

00:54:41.300 --> 00:54:42.780
They were going to take over
the world, all that.

00:54:42.780 --> 00:54:45.450
You ever see the film, "Rising
Sun," Michael Crichton?

00:54:45.450 --> 00:54:48.995
Possibly the most racist film
ever made in human history,

00:54:48.995 --> 00:54:49.900
but put that to one side.

00:54:49.900 --> 00:54:51.260
So Japan's going to take
everything over, blah, blah,

00:54:51.260 --> 00:54:52.680
blah, the rest of it.

00:54:52.680 --> 00:54:55.030
And then, of course, what
actually happens is they do

00:54:55.030 --> 00:54:56.800
the exchange rate thing, the
United States exchange rate

00:54:56.800 --> 00:54:59.210
goes down, the German one and
the Japanese one goes up.

00:54:59.210 --> 00:55:01.450
Now, the Japanese economy is
entirely export dependent.

00:55:01.450 --> 00:55:03.720
It's sort of like Germany
on steroids.

00:55:03.720 --> 00:55:05.850
So what they do is they move the
plant and equipment from

00:55:05.850 --> 00:55:08.900
the Japanese home islands out
to the second tier tigers.

00:55:08.900 --> 00:55:11.430
So you start to get investment
in Vietnam, Malaysia, all

00:55:11.430 --> 00:55:13.780
these places, and they move
the entire thing with the

00:55:13.780 --> 00:55:15.420
supplier networks,
the whole lot.

00:55:15.420 --> 00:55:17.190
Well, the way that the Japanese
welfare state was

00:55:17.190 --> 00:55:19.460
constructed, it was all
in-house to the firm.

00:55:19.460 --> 00:55:21.170
It was meant to be cradle
to grave, but the firm

00:55:21.170 --> 00:55:22.120
took care of you.

00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:24.460
Well, the firm has just broken
the social contract.

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:25.970
So how did people protect
themselves?

00:55:25.970 --> 00:55:28.140
They wanted another asset they
could have that would have a

00:55:28.140 --> 00:55:30.480
positive upside, that would
retain its value, and they

00:55:30.480 --> 00:55:31.680
could sell it in their
retirement.

00:55:31.680 --> 00:55:33.580
What did they buy en masse?

00:55:33.580 --> 00:55:34.460
Real estate.

00:55:34.460 --> 00:55:36.400
So you get a giant real
estate bubble.

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:38.860
The real estate bubble gets so
out of control that it popped

00:55:38.860 --> 00:55:40.830
and the banking system
can't support it.

00:55:40.830 --> 00:55:43.240
That collapses and that
starts the recession.

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:46.020
But the important part is
the sociological story.

00:55:46.020 --> 00:55:48.050
You've got a cultural and
generational shift.

00:55:48.050 --> 00:55:51.140
Because you've got a very old
population who are now 45

00:55:51.140 --> 00:55:53.130
years old, facing unemployment,
with a very,

00:55:53.130 --> 00:55:55.270
very narrow safety net
for the first time.

00:55:55.270 --> 00:55:57.330
So what do they do when the
government gives them money to

00:55:57.330 --> 00:55:59.880
spend to stimulate
the economy?

00:55:59.880 --> 00:56:01.830
They stick it under
the mattress.

00:56:01.830 --> 00:56:02.830
It doesn't go anywhere.

00:56:02.830 --> 00:56:03.790
It gets hoarded.

00:56:03.790 --> 00:56:05.340
So the savings rate goes up.

00:56:05.340 --> 00:56:06.520
And where do they
put the savings?

00:56:06.520 --> 00:56:08.170
In the post office account
and in the bank account.

00:56:08.170 --> 00:56:10.120
And what do the bank and the
post office do with it?

00:56:10.120 --> 00:56:11.660
They buy government bonds.

00:56:11.660 --> 00:56:13.440
So that's why you end
up with this massive

00:56:13.440 --> 00:56:14.720
extension in debt.

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:17.380
Now, the thing is, the Japanese
propensity to consume

00:56:17.380 --> 00:56:19.510
is really, really low,
particularly the higher up the

00:56:19.510 --> 00:56:20.880
demographic you get.

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:23.690
So 80-year-olds are not just
buying bonds and then

00:56:23.690 --> 00:56:25.660
liquidating them in retirement,
they're actually

00:56:25.660 --> 00:56:28.850
keeping them whole and handing
them onto the next generation.

00:56:28.850 --> 00:56:31.370
So you've got an
inter-generational debt

00:56:31.370 --> 00:56:32.830
transfer going on.

00:56:32.830 --> 00:56:36.890
So the story that basically it's
just a monetary policy

00:56:36.890 --> 00:56:39.460
story in, you know, Japan,
I think that's wrong.

00:56:39.460 --> 00:56:41.445
I think there's actually a
deeply structural problem

00:56:41.445 --> 00:56:43.240
that's going on there, and it
goes all the way back to the

00:56:43.240 --> 00:56:44.280
Plaza Accord.

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:47.200
So that's my short version of
Sven Steinmo's argument, but I

00:56:47.200 --> 00:56:48.836
find it quite convincing.

00:56:48.836 --> 00:56:51.325
AUDIENCE: How can an individual
state in the EU,

00:56:51.325 --> 00:56:54.150
like Ireland or something, try
to fix things for itself with

00:56:54.150 --> 00:56:55.580
all the constraints under it?

00:56:55.580 --> 00:56:56.600
MARK BLYTH: They can't.

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:58.800
Look, and it's good.

00:56:58.800 --> 00:57:00.050
Because you're in the Euro.

00:57:00.050 --> 00:57:01.780
So once you're in the
Euro, it's a kind

00:57:01.780 --> 00:57:03.110
of a one-time game.

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:05.340
Because the problem was if
you're Argentina and you tie

00:57:05.340 --> 00:57:08.046
yourself to the dollar, as they
did back in the day, back

00:57:08.046 --> 00:57:11.690
in the late 1990s into 2000, and
then you have the default.

00:57:11.690 --> 00:57:14.470
And they had a default because
Argentina is the graveyard of

00:57:14.470 --> 00:57:16.410
all bad economic policies
gone wrong, there's

00:57:16.410 --> 00:57:17.410
no doubt about that.

00:57:17.410 --> 00:57:19.900
But also because their major
trading partner is Brazil.

00:57:19.900 --> 00:57:22.830
And basically, the Real had a
40% exchange rate gain, and

00:57:22.830 --> 00:57:24.890
basically it screwed up all
their exports and the whole

00:57:24.890 --> 00:57:25.510
thing fell down.

00:57:25.510 --> 00:57:28.740
Now, because they were just on a
peg, they actually still had

00:57:28.740 --> 00:57:30.170
their own domestic currency.

00:57:30.170 --> 00:57:32.320
So they could go, to
hell with the peg.

00:57:32.320 --> 00:57:33.110
We've still got it.

00:57:33.110 --> 00:57:35.070
And then you lock up the banks
and people bang on the doors

00:57:35.070 --> 00:57:35.940
and all that sort of stuff.

00:57:35.940 --> 00:57:37.710
But you still have
your currency.

00:57:37.710 --> 00:57:40.500
Ireland doesn't have
a pound anymore.

